00:05:21.520 --> 00:05:23.970
So, you've probably heard
of the roentgen before.

00:05:23.970 --> 00:05:26.760
You've definitely seen
the roentgen as a unit

00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:30.810
because you've all looked in
those pen or pocket dosimeter

00:05:30.810 --> 00:05:32.820
that you actually had
at the nuclear reactor,

00:05:32.820 --> 00:05:35.970
when you guys took a tour of
it and controlled the control

00:05:35.970 --> 00:05:36.810
rods.

00:05:36.810 --> 00:05:39.810
The roentgen is not really a
unit that we use much anymore

00:05:39.810 --> 00:05:43.470
for very careful
calculations because you

00:05:43.470 --> 00:05:46.080
have to do some tissue
equivalency stuff

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:49.830
in order to go from
ionizations in air, which

00:05:49.830 --> 00:05:51.285
is what it actually
measures, it's

00:05:51.285 --> 00:05:55.500
the amount of charge
dissipated or built up in air,

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:58.320
to some damage to soft tissue.

00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:00.360
And the way you actually
calculate roentgens

00:06:00.360 --> 00:06:03.510
from first principles, linking
the physics and the biology

00:06:03.510 --> 00:06:06.540
part, is remember
this equation here?

00:06:06.540 --> 00:06:09.360
Stopping power, which
is some energy transfer,

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:12.270
divided by the energy
required to make an ion.

00:06:12.270 --> 00:06:15.510
Each one of those will give
one electron unit of charge

00:06:15.510 --> 00:06:18.040
towards [INAUDIBLE] coulombs.

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:20.400
And so this is the direct
link between the physics

00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:22.740
and the chemistry/biology
in this course.

00:06:22.740 --> 00:06:25.363
It's not something that's
done that carefully in any

00:06:25.363 --> 00:06:27.780
of the readings, which is why
I'm going to harp on it here

00:06:27.780 --> 00:06:29.070
in lecture.

00:06:29.070 --> 00:06:31.560
These two parts of the course
are often taught differently.

00:06:31.560 --> 00:06:33.420
And they're actually
totally related

00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:36.130
and everything's all the
same, which is kind of nice.

00:06:36.130 --> 00:06:39.260
You don't have to just relearn
a whole new lingo and field.

00:06:39.260 --> 00:06:41.060
Then there is the
SI units of dose.

00:06:41.060 --> 00:06:43.557
The ones that, when you do
calculations in the homework

00:06:43.557 --> 00:06:45.140
and the rest of your
life, I recommend

00:06:45.140 --> 00:06:48.410
that you use whenever
possible because they're

00:06:48.410 --> 00:06:52.100
in units that we're familiar
with, in standard units.

00:06:52.100 --> 00:06:54.370
The one where you start
with all along is the gray.

00:06:54.370 --> 00:06:59.240
A gray is the simple measure
of absorbed energy in joules

00:06:59.240 --> 00:07:01.850
per kilogram of whatever.

00:07:01.850 --> 00:07:05.130
And so calculating it is
fairly straightforward, too.

00:07:05.130 --> 00:07:08.420
For example, if you want to know
what sort of dose you would get

00:07:08.420 --> 00:07:11.690
in gray from
absorbing gamma rays,

00:07:11.690 --> 00:07:14.827
you can use this old
equation from the first third

00:07:14.827 --> 00:07:15.410
of the course.

00:07:20.660 --> 00:07:25.210
And if you integrate
this from, let's say,

00:07:25.210 --> 00:07:28.000
over the range of
whatever object or person

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:29.830
you happen to be
irradiating, you'll

00:07:29.830 --> 00:07:32.440
get some fractional
difference in intensity.

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:35.440
That, multiplied by the original
intensity of gammas, which

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:38.710
could be given in maybe
gamma rays per centimeter

00:07:38.710 --> 00:07:42.010
squared per second,
maybe times time

00:07:42.010 --> 00:07:44.590
to get total number of gammas
per centimeter squared.

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:53.420
All that multiplied by
the energy of each gamma,

00:07:53.420 --> 00:07:58.670
divided by the mass of whatever
is doing the absorbing,

00:07:58.670 --> 00:08:01.140
equals your dose in gray.

00:08:01.140 --> 00:08:03.840
So you can use all the old
stuff from the previous parts

00:08:03.840 --> 00:08:07.355
of the course directly to
calculate dose in gray.

00:08:07.355 --> 00:08:09.480
And this is the starting
point for any calculation.

00:08:09.480 --> 00:08:11.910
If you don't know what
tissue was exposed,

00:08:11.910 --> 00:08:15.390
what type of radiation provides
what biological effectiveness,

00:08:15.390 --> 00:08:16.230
it doesn't matter.

00:08:16.230 --> 00:08:19.130
You just start here.

00:08:19.130 --> 00:08:20.720
Then the other unit
you may have seen

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:22.820
is a unit, not of
energy absorption,

00:08:22.820 --> 00:08:25.430
but of increased risk
for something going

00:08:25.430 --> 00:08:27.470
wrong in the biological sense.

00:08:27.470 --> 00:08:29.030
It's called the sievert.

00:08:29.030 --> 00:08:33.039
For simple things like whole
body dose from gamma rays,

00:08:33.039 --> 00:08:35.900
sieverts equals
gray, because sievert

00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:39.500
is multiplied by this quality
factor, or this effectiveness

00:08:39.500 --> 00:08:40.549
factor.

00:08:40.549 --> 00:08:42.870
That Q factor is actually
a couple of factors.

00:08:42.870 --> 00:08:47.770
There's a Q for
the type of tissue

00:08:47.770 --> 00:08:49.610
and there's a Q for
the type of radiation.

00:08:53.780 --> 00:08:55.730
And the total quality
factor for whatever

00:08:55.730 --> 00:08:59.388
you're trying to calculate
is just the multiplication

00:08:59.388 --> 00:08:59.930
of these two.

00:09:07.835 --> 00:09:09.460
And so it's fairly
easy, if you're ever

00:09:09.460 --> 00:09:13.240
dealing with whole body gamma
dose, gray equals sieverts.

00:09:13.240 --> 00:09:16.180
If you're dealing with pretty
much anything different, gray

00:09:16.180 --> 00:09:17.290
does not equal sieverts.

00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:19.480
There'll be just some
factor to add in,

00:09:19.480 --> 00:09:21.280
which can be looked
up from a lookup table

00:09:21.280 --> 00:09:23.860
but, as I've told you before,
I don't like that explanation,

00:09:23.860 --> 00:09:25.120
look it up on a table.

00:09:25.120 --> 00:09:27.850
We're going to explore why the
lookup tables are constructed

00:09:27.850 --> 00:09:30.400
the way they are.

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:32.770
And then there's the
CGS units, the ones

00:09:32.770 --> 00:09:35.950
that are based in
centimeter-gram-second, instead

00:09:35.950 --> 00:09:39.150
of kilogram-meter-second.

00:09:39.150 --> 00:09:41.420
The rad is a simple measure.

00:09:41.420 --> 00:09:44.085
It's, let's say, 100
rad is just 1 gray.

00:09:44.085 --> 00:09:45.460
Where the rad
actually comes from

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:50.560
is, it's defined as 100 ergs
absorbed energy per gram,

00:09:50.560 --> 00:09:53.410
where an erg is 10
to the minus 7 joules

00:09:53.410 --> 00:09:56.843
and a gram is 10 to
the minus 3 kilograms.

00:09:56.843 --> 00:09:58.510
And so, you can do
the mental math there

00:09:58.510 --> 00:10:01.000
to make sure these all work out.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:04.120
And then a REM, a
roentgen equivalent man,

00:10:04.120 --> 00:10:06.850
is just a hundredth
of a sievert.

00:10:06.850 --> 00:10:08.950
So there's historical
basis for this.

00:10:08.950 --> 00:10:11.380
Back in the day, more
folks used CGS units.

00:10:11.380 --> 00:10:13.660
There's been a push
to SI units, which

00:10:13.660 --> 00:10:16.225
I happen to like because
everything works out

00:10:16.225 --> 00:10:18.100
and you don't have to
remember things like 10

00:10:18.100 --> 00:10:21.530
to the minus 7 joules
or whatever like that.

00:10:21.530 --> 00:10:24.130
So I'd say, when in doubt,
for equal comparisons

00:10:24.130 --> 00:10:26.740
always use the SI
units and always

00:10:26.740 --> 00:10:28.330
start with the
gray because that's

00:10:28.330 --> 00:10:31.420
something where you can take a
physical calculation of energy

00:10:31.420 --> 00:10:35.860
per kilogram and go into
some increased cancer risk

00:10:35.860 --> 00:10:38.630
by using the dose
quality factors.

00:10:38.630 --> 00:10:41.620
So let's take a look
at how these appear.

00:10:41.620 --> 00:10:43.930
First of all, gammas,
x-rays, electrons,

00:10:43.930 --> 00:10:46.630
positrons of any LET.

00:10:46.630 --> 00:10:49.870
LET, as I mentioned before,
is linear energy transfer.

00:10:58.267 --> 00:10:59.850
And to put this
mathematically, you've

00:10:59.850 --> 00:11:06.020
actually seen this before, which
would be some change in energy

00:11:06.020 --> 00:11:09.850
over some change in distance.

00:11:09.850 --> 00:11:11.660
It's the stopping power.

00:11:11.660 --> 00:11:14.660
It's not like the stopping
power, it's the stopping power.

00:11:14.660 --> 00:11:17.660
So with the formulas you got in
the second half of this class,

00:11:17.660 --> 00:11:20.600
you can calculate
linear energy transfer.

00:11:20.600 --> 00:11:25.670
Now, why are these things given
in, let's say, discrete tables,

00:11:25.670 --> 00:11:30.380
or now what's currently
recommended is these functions?

00:11:30.380 --> 00:11:31.510
Does anyone have any idea?

00:11:38.480 --> 00:11:40.100
How many of your
Core Seven friends

00:11:40.100 --> 00:11:44.380
know the formula for stopping
power, or could parse it even,

00:11:44.380 --> 00:11:45.840
or understand it?

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:48.090
You don't have to,
not everybody has to.

00:11:48.090 --> 00:11:52.470
So, for the rest of us, there
are simpler empirical relations

00:11:52.470 --> 00:11:55.350
or relations that get the
numbers right that aren't

00:11:55.350 --> 00:11:58.110
necessarily based on physics.

00:11:58.110 --> 00:11:59.760
So a simple lookup
table, for those

00:11:59.760 --> 00:12:02.895
who don't have time to take
22.01 or something beyond,

00:12:02.895 --> 00:12:04.020
is the easiest thing to do.

00:12:04.020 --> 00:12:05.310
And in most cases it works.

00:12:05.310 --> 00:12:08.310
It's not exact, but it's
probably close enough.

